Supervised_Learning Project - by Chirag Lodaya¶

Objective: To predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.¶

Data Description: The file Bank.xls contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.¶

Domain: Banking¶

Context: This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with minimal budget.¶

Attribute Information:¶

ID : Customer ID¶

Age : Customer's age in completed years¶

Experience : #years of professional experience¶

Income : Annual income of the customer in *dollar 000¶

ZIP Code : Home Address ZIP code.¶

Family : Family size of the customer¶

CCAvg : Avg. spending on credit cards per month in *dollar 000¶

Education : Education Level. - Undergrad, Graduate or Advanced/Professional¶

Mortgage : Value of house mortgage if any. in *dollar 000¶

Personal Loan : Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?¶

Securities Account : Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?¶

CD Account : Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?¶

Online : Does the customer use internet banking facilities?¶

Credit card : Does the customer use a credit card issued by UniversalBank?¶

dfExp = data.loc[data['Experience'] >0]
negExp = data.Experience < 0
column_name = 'Experience'
mylist = data.loc[negExp]['ID'].tolist() 
for id in mylist:
    age = data.loc[np.where(data['ID']==id)]["Age"].tolist()[0]
    education = data.loc[np.where(data['ID']==id)]["Education"].tolist()[0]
    df_filtered = dfExp[(dfExp.Age == age) & (dfExp.Education == education)]
    exp = df_filtered['Experience'].median()
    data.loc[data.loc[np.where(data['ID']==id)].index, 'Experience'] = exp
print("Negative data after changes:",data[data['Experience'] < 0]['Experience'].count())

- From the pairplot, Here are the findings:¶

Experience is normally distributed with the value starting from 8 years. Mean is equal to median. There are negative values in the Experience, which we have corrected in the previous step¶

Income is positively skewed. Majority people fall in the range of 45K- 55K. Supporting our argument here as mean is greater than mode¶

CCAvg is also a positively skewed and most value lies in the range 0K- 10K and most of it less than 2.5K¶

Mortgage, mostly 3/4th people o have a mortgage < 40K.¶

The variables family and education are ordinal variables. The distribution of families is evenly distributes¶

- Influence of income and education on personal loan:¶

It is evident that people whose education is 1 have higher income, but also people who have taken loans have a similar income¶

- Influence of income and Mortgage on personal loan¶

From the graph it is evident that people who have taken loans have higher mortgage and those who have not have a lower mortgage¶

- Influence of Securities account on personal loan:¶

We can say that people who dont have a Security account in the bank have taken loans¶

- Influence of Family members on personal loan¶

As it can be seen, there is not a solid inference we can have from the graph, but we can ,mildly say that family member of 3 and more are likely to take loans(higher rate)¶

- Influence of CD account on personal loan¶

Here we can see people who dont have CD account do not have loan, but people who have CD account, majoritily have taken loans¶

- Influnce of CCavg on personal loan¶

Blue is not taken loan and orange is taken loan, we can say from the graph that, people who have taken loans have a higer credit card usage average as compared to the people who have not taken loans.¶

- Next we see the heat map (Correlation):¶

- Age and experience are highly correlated (positve) as its common knowledge that as age increase, work experience increases¶

- CCAVG and Income is moderately correlated(Positive), as this is common knowledge, with increse in income, credit card limits increase and spending becomes more¶

model = LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear")
model.fit(x_train, y_train)
#predict on test
y_predict = model.predict(x_test)
coef_df = pd.DataFrame(model.coef_)
coef_df['intercept'] = model.intercept_
print("Co effeciencts of the Logistic regression model\n\n", coef_df)
model_score = model.score(x_test, y_test)
print("\n\nAccuracy of Logistic regression model", model_score*100, "%")

loan_model = GaussianNB()
loan_model.fit(x_train, y_train.ravel())
loan_train_predict = loan_model.predict(x_train)
loan_test_predict = loan_model.predict(x_test)
print("\n\nAccuracy of Naive Bayes Model: {0:.4f}".format(metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, loan_test_predict)*100), "%")


NNH = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors= 5 , weights = 'distance' )
NNH.fit(x_train, y_train)
predicted_labels = NNH.predict(x_test)
print("\n\nAccuracy of KNN model:", NNH.score(x_test, y_test)*100, "%")

In [9]:
x=data.drop(['ID','Experience'], axis=1)
y=x['Personal Loan']
x=x.drop(['Personal Loan'], axis=1)
models = []
LogisticRegression
models.append(('Logistic', LogisticRegression()))
models.append(('KNN', KNeighborsClassifier()))
models.append(('Naive Bayes', GaussianNB()))

results = []
names = []
scoring = 'accuracy'
for name, model in models:
	kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=12345)
	cv_results = model_selection.cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
	results.append(cv_results)
	names.append(name)
	msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
	print(msg)
# boxplot algorithm comparison
fig = plt.figure()
fig.suptitle('Algorithm Comparison')
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
plt.boxplot(results)
ax.set_xticklabels(names)
plt.show()

In the above block of code we compare the algorithms.¶

As we can see the accuracy do not have much differece¶

But according to our result it is best that we choose Logistic Regression as it has the highest accuracy¶

The main reason for this would be, Logistic regression is a faster algoritm and here our analysis suggest that it also has an higher accuracy. Hence we get speed(as it is one of the advanatges of Logistic regression) and also here it gives out the best accuracy as well.¶

Also knn would be preferable if there was a lot of correlation in the data¶

But as we saw in our above EDA, correlation is not very high¶

also naive bayes could be a choice, if training examples were few, but then here we have decent amoun of tuples/rows, hence it is the best choice to go with the model of higest accuracy and also good speed¶

Hence we choose Logistic regression as our final model for the appliacation.¶
